## 4️⃣ Why Choose Vov = 0.25V?

Overdrive voltage:

Vov = VGS − Vth

Trade-off considerations:

### If Vov is very small:
✔ High gain (since gm = 2ID/Vov increases)  
❌ Poor matching  
❌ More sensitive to noise  
❌ Slower speed  

### If Vov is large:
✔ Better speed  
✔ Better robustness  
❌ Lower gain  
❌ Higher power  

0.25V is chosen because:

- It ensures strong inversion operation
- Provides reasonable gm
- Maintains saturation margin
- Good compromise between gain & speed

---

## 5️⃣ What is Minimum Overdrive Voltage We Can Apply?

Theoretically:
Vov → very small gives very high gm

Practically in 180nm:

Minimum Vov ≈ 0.15V – 0.2V

If Vov < 0.15V:
- Device enters weak inversion
- gm formula changes
- Current becomes exponential
- Design becomes unstable

Hence:

Vov = 0.25V ensures strong inversion operation.

---

## 6️⃣ Why gm = 2ID / Vov?

In strong inversion saturation region:

ID = (1/2) µnCox (W/L) Vov²

Differentiating w.r.t VGS:

gm = ∂ID/∂VGS  
gm = µnCox (W/L) Vov  

But:

ID = (1/2) µnCox (W/L) Vov²  

So,

gm = 2ID / Vov

This formula is valid only in strong inversion saturation.

---

## 7️⃣ Why ro = 1 / (λID)?

Due to channel length modulation:

ID increases slightly with VDS.

Small signal output resistance:

ro = 1 / (λID)

Smaller λ → larger ro → higher gain.

---

## 8️⃣ Why Gain Reduces with Source Degeneration?

With Rs:

Effective transconductance:

gm_eff = gm / (1 + gmRs)

Thus gain reduces because:

Av = -gm(ro) / (1 + gmRs)

So degeneration improves:

✔ Linearity  
✔ Stability  

But reduces gain.

---

## 9️⃣ Why Circuit B Has Lowest Gain?

Because:

Current source transistor introduces small-signal resistance:

Reff ≈ 1/gm3

This adds extra degeneration.

Hence denominator increases → gain decreases.

---

## 🔟 Why Circuit C Has Highest Gain?

Because:

Diode-connected NMOS:

Rd ≈ 1/gm

Which is smaller than current source degeneration.

Thus:

Less degeneration  
Higher effective gm  
Higher voltage gain  

